My page started out as a yoga photography page, and if you have been here since then, I thank you heartily 😂I think it's important as a human to keep challenging yourself, exploring what makes you curious, and my page has followed me down the wider path of movement photography - whether it be pole, calisthenics, circus, dance.  I honestly love it all.  But I'm using this post to say heyyyyyy I'm still shooting my OG love yoga photography - now also making reels and specialized content creation.  I appreciate my peoples who have worked with me for years now; I think that if curating a social media presence is a goal, that it's important to build a relationship with photographers/videographers who understand what you are doing and can help achieve that goal.  So please reach out if you'd like to book a session.  I'll be in London/Paris in February, Vegas in April and let's see where else 2023 takes me!

Mini HSP: Meet Renee Choi
⁠
Words and Pictures: Renee (@reneechoiphotography)⁠
Artists: Ugi (@ugithecontortionist), Valentin (@valentin_chetverkin), Jessica (@russian.r3d) and Anna (@anna_ivaseva)

Renee has been focusing on movement photography for the past 8 years, starting with her completion of yoga teacher training and from there combining yoga and photography.
Yoga photography introduced her to contortion photography, which then expanded into the vast world of circus photography.
Renee is probably the least flexible person you will ever meet, and her own limitations fuel her interest in strength and flexibility and what can be accomplished with consistency and dedication.

HSP: How did you become a physical movement specialized photographer?
RC: I finished my yoga teacher training at a time when social media for yoga teachers was really kicking off, and everyone was realizing that they needed a social media presence. I had no shortage of yoga teachers to photograph, and some of them have a lot of strength and flexibility. I find that different movement styles beget each other, so from yoga photography, it was a natural progression to all types of movement.

HSP: Where do you find inspiration?
RC: From the people I photograph, the location we are at, and the light at that moment. Everyone’s movement is so unique, so I try and capture what makes them who they are, while at the same time taking into account where we are and what light we have to play with. I feel honored with everyone I work with, that they trust me to capture what they love doing.

HSP: How has your style changed over time?
RC: I would say my photo editing has improved a lot, but I’ve also started incorporating a lot more video. I think it’s important to keep expanding creatively and video offers a different way to story tell. Even though both photos and videos take up their own space in art, I think I will always be a photographer at heart!

I love sunrise shoots.  I love being out when a lot of people are still sleeping and I like being in areas that are typically crowded when they are empty.  Somehow @rebeccahannah_ convinced me that this location would be quiet mid-morning because "everyone will be at work." And she was right - it was empty except for the fashion influencer with her instagram boyfriend shooting her Dior bag, the family whose mom clapped for Rebecca after we took these photos, the couple who helped stop all the foot traffic crossing in front of our shot, and very other tourist who saw us shooting here and had the same idea.  Basically I learned my lesson and now everyone can expect sunrise shoots...forever 😂

The Beginning.

Of bending over backwards - deeper, stronger, with more control - for myself.

Of less compromising and more organic alignment.

Harmonized dance between body and mind.

Prayer - channeled and intentional.  Creation - pure and free.

Of space - to be exactly as I am, moment to moment.  Honestly.

***

When I first wrote the words ‘The Beginning’ my negative mind scoffed at myself.  How many beginnings am I going to have?  I sat with that.

And I came to realize what a gift all of these beginnings were, and how much has evolved with every one.  How natural and necessary it is to recommit to ourselves over and over again on this journey of becoming and unbecoming all that we are.

My heart glowed as I recognized my own steps forward and steps back, on a journey that I am proud to call my own.

I let my positive mind rest of found neutrality.  Exactly where I am in this moment.

The Beginning.  Just where I’m meant to be.

***

Photoshop AI is getting better with each update.  Image #3 is how the photo of @cassandra.fierce looks right after color correction.  You can see where her pants split completely along the front to back seam 😅(A moment of silence for the hot pink Zara pants casualty )Image #2 I used AI to repair the pants.  Then I was like, I wonder what AI can do about the man.  And you can see AI completely rebuilt the car in the first image 🤯Not sure about others, but I've been using AI more to clean up my images, more than content aware fill and clone which I used to really love.  Granted it still needs a lot of work - like I've had issues where it tried to reconstruct hands and wound up making my model's hands look like troll hands or missing/distorted fingers or stumps for hands 😂Overall I'm really happy with this shot, as I only had the one take before the pants were no more 🪦I'm also impressed with Cassandra's pro face as she felt her pants rip - you know she felt that breeze come through but her face didn't change🤣
.

One of the most amazing places I’ve been - #tolantongo The water is a natural thermal spring - it’s like heated bathwater warm - and the color comes from the minerals in the rocks.  @rebeccahannah_ and I booked an @airbnb local tour for the long day - it’s about 3.5 hours outside #mexicocity  We crammed into a car with two other Americans (and our driver, who told us he and his wife are swingers) and off we went!  I have to admit, when I saw the light and number of people, I was like 😮‍💨because I knew I’d have my editing cut out for me.  The difference between light and shadow for the exposure was pretty big.  And, according to our tour guide, the number of people that day was “not so much” (pro tip:  go during the weekday, not weekend) but I don’t think he was thinking about editing 😂
Image 1, 4, 7:  straight out of camera, using photoshop AI, clone and patch for people removal
Image 2, 5, 8:  export after color and exposure adjustments in lightroom
Image 3, 6, 9:  straight out of camera
Image 10:  just rebecca in a bikini because why not
